<HEADLINE>
Help! Abusive/unethical tactics by long distance company
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<POST>
<POSTER> Grant </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2003-03-25T01:71:00 </POSTDATE>
Email: Grant &lt;gpe ... @aos.wisc.edu&gt;
Groups: misc.legal, misc.consumers, alt.consumers.experiences, alt.consumers


1. A few weeks ago, a representative from a *major* long distance
carrier used a blatant lie to trick me into making a recorded statement
on the telephone that could be construed as authorizing a switch to
their service. Basically, the representative told me (*told*, not
*implied*!) that their records showed that they had been our
longstanding long distance provider, but that another company had tried
to switch us without our authorization. He asked me to confirm, for
their records, that I intended to &quot;stay&quot; with their service, so that
they could block the switch. Since I do not normally handle our
telephone bills, I took his statement at face value and gave them the
statement they wanted (characteristically, as we later found out, it was
taken by a different operator who hadn't made the initial
misrepresentation to me). After hanging up, my wife informed me that
they had *never* been our long distance provider, and that she had
already had to fend off several similar ploys from the same company in
previous weeks.

2. I *immediately* contacted our current local phone service, explained
the situation, and told them that I definitely did *not* want to switch
to the other carrier. The representative told me they could definitely
block the switch if I just provided her with either my birth date or the
last four digits of my social security number to confirm that I was who
I said I was (which I did). We assumed at that point that the matter was
settled.

3. The following month, we received a phone bill that included long
distance charges from the carrier mentioned in 1. It included something
like $140 for a 1.5 hour call overseas --- approximately TEN times the
rate we normally pay!!

4. We immediately contacted the long distance carrier in question and
protested the exorbitant charge, and protested the fact that we had been
switched in the first place based on a blatant misrepresentation. In
addition to the manner in which we had been switched in the first place,
we had never been advised of any unusual rates that would apply to
overseas calls. After *several hours* of arguing in vain with one
representative after another, we finally spoke with someone who agreed
to reduce the charge to what we normally would have paid with our
&quot;normal&quot; carrier. She even gave us a confirmation number!

5. This morning (just a couple of weeks later), we received a call from
a collection agency concerning the $140 charge. He claimed to be
unimpressed by our story or by the confirmation number cited above.

6. We called the carrier again, and they claimed to have no record of
any discussions of the type described under 4. They claimed to only
have our original recorded statement authorizing the switch (see 1.).
We told them that if that was the case, then we would have no choice but
to record all future conversations with them. The representative
claimed that would be illegal. We said it wouldn't be if we informed
them, and if they didn't like it, they could hang up and all future
exchanges with us would have to be in writing.

That's where it stands, as of today. We are at wit's end. This morning,
after talking to the long distance company again, my wife was in tears
from anger and frustration.

The above story only gives the highlights. We have been lied to, and
sometimes even verbally abused, again and again whenever we spoke to
company representatives, and it now appears to be *beyond our ability*
to permanently regain control of who our long distance carrier is, let
alone whether we have to pay that exorbitant bill. We can't even trust
our own local phone service to block a change, even when they assure us
that they *will* block the change. And we are absolutely appalled that
what we had previously thought of as a reputable, well-known long
distance company would resort to these kinds of tactics in the first place.

Now, of course, we are also concerned about what they will do to our
credit report if we refuse to pay the charge.

Our instinct is to contact the FTC and file a formal complaint. But we
are deterred by two things: (1) our inability to document *in detail*
many of the conversations that took place (it never occurred to us that
the company would intentionally, and repeatedly, disregard our wishes,
or misrepresent their own actions), and (2) our sense that regulatory
oversight of large corporations is not exactly a high priority in
Washington right now.

Complicating matters is the fact that the company passed us around to
many different representatives on the phone in a way that seemed to us
to be deliberately calculated to destroy any continuity in (or
reconstructable record of) the discussion or handling of our case, and
to give each representative &quot;plausible deniability&quot; regarding what
transpired in the previous conversation. Much of the time we have spent
on the phone has consisted of repeating, for the umpteenth time, the
details of what we had just told a previous representative!

The second instinct is to try to find other customers with similar
stories and see whether some kind of punitive civil action could be
initiated against companies that engage in this kind of behavior.
Unfortunately, we certainly don't have the resources to take on a huge
corporation on our own, so we're hoping there is an agency or firm
(public or private) with both the ability and the desire to expose and
punish these kinds of consumer abuses.

The third instinct is to try to embarrass the company in some kind of
public forum; e.g., by sicing the press on them. But we realize that
the likelihood of our particular case, taken in isolation, arousing the
interest of a 60 Minutes-type show is zilch. What would be needed is a
gaggle of victims with nearly identical stories, combined with some
interest on the part of the press in going after a big name corporation.
Fat chance.

Hoping that someone here can see an effective avenue that we're not
seeing. If we roll over on this one, where will it end?

