Grant,

I believe you. It looks like you were scammed, and slammed. The whole
system has been deregulated. Even major carriers are apparently doing
this stuff. A major carrier (Sprint) did similar to me last year.

The scam varies, but with the same idea... lies, confusion whatever
it takes to induce a consent. After that the new carrier basically
crams anything they can get away with onto your bill.
The agreement to reduce the bill followed by flat refusal or denial
also appears part of the game.
You thought they were in the telecom biz?? Such Naievity!

People who have international calls appear especially targeted, since
the default rates are $3-6 min, and the scam can yield a fair
amount of money for the carrier... $300 - $3000 per.
After all, a $30 scam is hardly worth doing, right?

If you roll, it doesn't end. Its impractical to sue them, its probably

impractical for them to sue you. If you don't owe the charge, perhaps
you shouldn't pay it. They might slam your credit and refuse to do
business with you in future.

The dispute resolution procedure you encountered is more fraud. They
agree to reduce the charges, to delay and wear you down, then deny
it.They make sure its your word against their records.
Its pretty outrageous.

The most important thing to remember is.... don't be too upset, its
part of the world. There are scamsters and criminals in the world,
even in high corporate offices. Especially in the telecom industry.
So the wife should stop crying, its not her or your fault.

Its probably not productive to call them again. Their dispute
resolution is more scam. Pay them, sue them, or deny the charge
in writing and wait for them to sue you.

Whatever you choose, you might consider refering the matter to the
FBI re wire fraud. See if they have any interest in the matter.
Send them this post and the particulars. Let folks here know what
happens. Don't tell the carrier.

Good luck.

